In favour of the end of the year un. 74 as the date of the meeting made famous in the Dsalagru, a certain amount of additional evidence is derived from various allusions in the body of the treatise itself. Thus at 17. aa reference is made to the last largess which had been given to the people (praxinus quriiem congiaria ipsi uidistis plerasque senes, uc.) as something within recent memory: it is known to have been given by Titus in 73. Again in 37. 1 Mucianus is spoken of as alive and at work over a collection of speeches belonging to the republican period. Now from a passage in Pliny (N. H. xxxii. 6, 62), in which he is referred to in the past tense, it has been argued, with great probability that in an. 77-the year in which Pliny presented his Natural Histary to Titus -Mucianus was no longer alive (see Teuffel-Schwabe, §§ 313-4). This would seem at least to narrow the range of choice to one of the years preceding that date—as an upper limit. For the lower limit, mention ’ may be made of the use of nuper² at 5. 30, referring to an appearance made by Eprius Marcellus before the senate, probably in the year nn. 70. Another reference to the same individual, along with Vibius Crispus, points more definitely to the year 74 itself: nunc principes iu Caesaris amicitia agunt feruntque cuncta (8. 18).
